I am pretty sure, that your item inherits from ItemBase. So if you want to use something from ItemBase, there is no need to cast it.

But with many functions, the item is passed as EntityAI, for example.
If you need a specific function, that doesn't exist in EntityAI, you need to downcast the item.

Here is a little example from my fridge.
When you put food in the fridge's inventory, the decaytimer will be multiplied by a factor.

The item, that enters the inventory will be passed to the function as EntityAI. Food inherits from EntityAI... later from ItemBase and finally from EdibleBase.

But the decaytimer is a EdibleBase thing. It doesn't exist in ItemBase or EntityAI.

So I need to Downcast the item to EdibleBase before I can call the required functions. (like GetDecayTimer() or SetDecayTimer()

```override void EECargoIn(EntityAI item)
    {        
        super.EECargoIn( item );

        Edible_Base Food = Edible_Base.Cast( item );

        if ( Food && !Food.IsInFridge() )
        {
            float old_decay_timer = Food.GetDecayTimer();
            float new_decay_timer;
            int factor = GetBLPalletConfig().FridgeDecayFactor;

            if ( factor > 0)
            {
                new_decay_timer = old_decay_timer * factor;
            }
            else
            {
                new_decay_timer = old_decay_timer;
            }

            Food.SetDecayTimer( new_decay_timer );
            Food.SetInFridge( true );
        }
    }```

